{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"65c8976b-e0bb-411a-9e9d-88851cdb4cc2","content":"Your project is set up perfectly. The `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.HotReload` package lets you run tests in a watch mode — tests automatically re-run when you save file changes.\n\n**Usage:**\n\n```bash\ndotnet test --hotreload\n```\n\nThis starts the test runner in hot-reload mode. It runs your tests, then waits. When you edit and save a file, it re-runs automatically — no need to restart.\n\n**Your current situation:** The `IsValidEmail` method only checks for empty strings but doesn't check for `@`, so `Validate_MissingAtSign_ReturnsFalse` will fail. You can start hot-reload mode, then fix `IsValidEmail` to include an `@` check, save, and see the tests re-run instantly.\n\nWant me to start the hot-reload session and fix the failing test?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b4c056c4-47fe-48bf-8fb6-9d4fc3a120f8","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user has a test project with `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.HotReload` already referenced. They want to know how to use the hot reload feature to quickly iterate on fixes.\n\nLooking at the tests:\n1. `Validate_ValidEmail_ReturnsTrue` - calls `IsValidEmail(\"user@example.com\")` expecting true → `IsValidEmail` checks `!string.IsNullOrEmpty(email)` → returns true ✅\n2. `Validate_MissingAtSign_ReturnsFalse` - calls `IsValidEmail(\"userexample.com\")` expecting false → returns true (not empty) ❌ FAIL\n\n\n3. `Validate_EmptyString_ReturnsFalse` - calls `IsValidEmail(\"\")` expecting false → returns false ✅\n\nThe `IsValidEmail` method is too simplistic—it only checks if the string is non-empty, so it won't catch the missing `@` sign case. To use the HotReload extension, I can run `dotnet test --watch` which automatically re-runs tests whenever code changes are saved, letting the user quickly fix the validation logic and see results without manual restarts.","outputTokens":622,"requestId":"2027:239FAB:3C99933:42534F3:6A02EBC